# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: humpty-dumpty
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] 5–6 in the first edition, is illustrated by a drawing of three children and signed "A.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] R., Sr." A rhyming poem in four stanzas, it indicates that the story originated years ago when "unreasonable children three" would accept nothing but the Wonderland of Alice.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] Richards was the mother, who gave them more of what they knew and loved.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] Now grown up, one of them made the pictures.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] With apology to Tenniel and Carroll ("We're not original, nor wise, nor witty"), they plead for mercy from the Critic.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] The 2009 Evertype edition credits mother and daughter under their full names Alice Matlack Richards (1835–1900) and Anna Richards Brewster.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] Brewster, whose given middle name was Mary, not Matlack, became a renowned artist under her married name.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] According to Carolyn Sigler, Anna Matlack was already known as a poet and playwright before she married William Trost Richards in 1856, age 20 or 21.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] In the 1890s she wrote comic poems that were published in American children's magazines.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] *A New Alice* was "an expanded version of the stories she had invented for her young children, to whom the novel is dedicated, about their favorite storybook world." A second edition was published in 1896.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-new-alice-in-the-old-wonderland] Sigler interpolates, "Alice Lee—Richards's protagonist as well as her daughter, who is fictionalized in the text".
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-twisted-tale] Available in the UK but no US release date at this time.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-twisted-tale] A graphic novel version of the 2018 book *Part of Your World*, adapted by Stephanie Kate Strohm, was released on June 13, 2023.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-twisted-tale] A graphic novel version of the 2020 book *Straight On Till Morning*, also adapted by Stephanie Kate Strohm, was released on June 11, 2024.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-twisted-tale] A graphic novel version of the 2016 book *As Old As Time*, adapted by Beatrice Bassoli and Francesca Siviero, was released on May 6, 2025, and published on Webtoon on October 17.
[src:humpty-dumpty/a-twisted-tale] A graphic novel version of the 2022 book *Almost There*, adapted by Jamila Rowser, was also announced, though its release date is currently unknown.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby wants very much to be in her own fairy tale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Elmo takes an interest in Abby's wish and tells her the story of "Alice in Wonderland".
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] For a second Abby falls asleep and she opens her eyes to see that she is wearing a blue dress and blouse and Elmo has turned into a rabbit and is in a great hurry.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] At the bottom, she loses her wand to Mr.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit, who disappears at the end of the tunnel.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby notices there is a small door, but it's locked.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] She finds the key to the door on a table that just appeared.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] She unlocks the door, but she's too big to fit through the little door.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] With that she closes, locks the door and puts the key back on the table.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Then Abby notices there is a bottle that just appeared.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Before Abby can drink it, the bottle tells her not to drink him, but say things that rhyme with 'drink'.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby does and she shrinks to the right size to go through the door, but she recalls she locked it and left the key on the table, where it is out of her reach.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby finds a cookie who tells her to say things that rhyme with 'eat'.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby says so many rhymes, she grows pretty big, but she manages to balance her size, grab the key and shrink herself to a small size.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby takes Bottle and Cookie with her as she unlocks the door and enters a flowerbed.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Further in the flowerbed, Abby meets the Counterpillar (played by Count von Count) and his partner Little Rose-ita (played by Rosita), but does not want to join in their counting game.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] With Cookie's help, Abby restores herself to her regular size.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit rushes past and Abby runs after him, passing Tweedle-Dee and Tweedle-Dum (played by Bert and Ernie, respectively), whom the former tells the latter that they are actually not in this story.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby bumps into a tree and meets the Cheshire Cookie Cat (played by Cookie Monster), who points her in the direction of a tea party.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] At the tea party, Abby meets the Mad Hatter (played by Grover), Mr.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] To Abby's surprise, the Hatter doesn't serve tea, but letters 'T' in the cups.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] The Hatter shows Abby his collection of hats.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit for her wand, but with the hole in his pocket, he dropped it somewhere.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] The Cheshire Cookie Cat appears, guzzles up all the scones and cookies and scares away Mousie.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby walks down a path in the search for her wand until she sees the path forks into four directions.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit comes to talk with Abby, she sits down in despair of being lost in this wonderland.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit rushes off to attend the King's Croquet Game.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby follows him and finds a door in a tree.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] The door takes her to the messy castle of the king, "The Grouch of Cards" (played by Oscar the Grouch).
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] The king has Abby's wand thinking it's a new royal scepter.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby tries to retrieve her wand, challenging the king to a game of croquet, but he cheats.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit protests at the king's decision to keep the wand.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Before his grouchlings can throw out Abby and Mr.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit, they both use Cookie to grow large.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] They scare the grouchlings and the king away.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit restore themselves to their original size, Abby reclaims her wand.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Abby is unable to magic herself back home, but Mr.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Rabbit reminds her she's still dreaming.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Back in Sesame Street, Elmo shakes Abby awake.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Although Abby sort of got her wish to be in a fairy tale, she thinks she's better off being in a fairy tale when she's a little older.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Additional Muppets performed by Pam Arciero, John Kennedy, Peter Linz, Paul McGinnis, Martin P.
[src:humpty-dumpty/abby-in-wonderland] Robinson, David Stephens, and Matt Vogel.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] Each episode begins with Alice facing different problems and consulting with her cat Dinah.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] In order to find the answer she needs to get through a situation, she goes through her mirror that takes her to Wonderland where she partakes in surreal adventures with its inhabitants that revolve around the situation that she is dealing with at home.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] Every episode features singing and dancing.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] The series originally ran from March 23, 1992 to 1995 (with reruns continuing until at least 1998) on The Disney Channel and on stations across the country.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] *Adventures in Wonderland* was originally taped at Disney-MGM Studios at the Walt Disney World Resort in Bay Lake, Florida, with two sound stages used exclusively for the show, for its first 40 episodes.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] Afterward, shooting was moved to Los Angeles, California.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] The Cheshire Cat and Dormouse puppets were created by Chiodo Bros.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] Buena Vista Home Video released three volumes of certain episodes on VHS in 1993.
[src:humpty-dumpty/adventures-in-wonderland-1992-tv-series] The series was made available for streaming on Disney+ on April 30, 2021.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He served as Lord Advocate, the senior Law Officer of Scotland, before becoming Lord Justice General and Lord President of the Court of Session, the head of the country's judiciary.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He was then appointed a Lord of Appeal in Ordinary (Law Lord) and became a Justice of the Supreme Court when the judicial functions of the House of Lords were transferred to that Court.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] Alan Rodger was born on 18 September 1944 in Glasgow, to Professor T Ferguson Rodger, Professor of Psychological Medicine at the University of Glasgow, and Jean Margaret Smith Chalmers, and educated at the private Kelvinside Academy in the city.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He studied at the University of Glasgow, graduating with an MA, and at the University's School of Law, taking an LLB.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He then studied at New College, Oxford—under David Daube, Regius Professor of Civil Law—where he graduated with an MA (by decree) and DPhil, and was Dyke Junior Research Fellow at Balliol College, Oxford, from 1969 to 1970 and a Fellow of New College from 1970 to 1972.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He became an advocate in 1974 and was Clerk of the Faculty of Advocates from 1976 to 1979.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He was a Member of the Mental Welfare Commission for Scotland from 1981 to 1984, and was appointed Queen's Counsel in 1985.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] Rodger was appointed a Senator of the College of Justice, a judge of the High Court of Justiciary and Court of Session, in 1995, He became Lord Justice General and Lord President in 1996.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He was appointed a Lord of Appeal in Ordinary in 2001, upon the retirement of Lord Clyde, in which capacity his Judicial Assistants included Charles Banner.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He and nine other Lords of Appeal in Ordinary became Justices of the Supreme Court upon that body's inauguration on 1 October 2009.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] Lord Rodger of Earlsferry died from a brain tumour at a hospice in Clydebank on 26 June 2011, at the age of 66.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] Scottish First Minister Alex Salmond, who provoked fury after criticising Rodger less than a month earlier, said he had made an "outstanding contribution" to Scottish public life.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] Lord Rodger of Earlsferry was elected a Fellow of the British Academy in 1991, and the same year was the Maccabaean Lecturer at the Academy.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He was appointed a Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, an Honorary Bencher at Lincoln's Inn in 1992, and an Honorary Bencher of the Inn of Court of Northern Ireland in 1998.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He was appointed an Honorary Member of SPTL, subsequently SLS in 1992 and a Corresponding Member of Bayerische Akademy der Wissenschaften in 2001.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He was President of the Holdsworth Club in 1998–99 and made an Honorary Fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers in 2008.
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] He received honorary degrees of Doctor of Laws (LLD) from the Universities of Glasgow (1995), Aberdeen (1999) and Edinburgh (2001).
[src:humpty-dumpty/alan-rodger] Lord Rodger of Earlsferry had been the Visitor of St Hugh's College, Oxford, since 2003, High Steward of the University of Oxford since 2008, and an Honorary Professor at the University of Glasgow School of Law since July 2009.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] As with most beers, ale typically has a bittering agent to balance the malt and act as a preservative.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Ale was originally bittered with gruit, a mixture of herbs or spices boiled in the wort before fermentation, before hops replaced gruit as the bittering agent.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In England, however, it was also common to brew ale without adding herbs.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The word *ale* comes into English from its ancestor-language, Proto-Germanic.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] English belongs to the West Germanic branch of Proto-Germanic, and some other languages in this branch also attest to the word: Middle Dutch *āle* and *ael*, and the Old Saxon word *alo-fat* 'ale-cup'.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The word is also found throughout the North Germanic languages, almost certainly appearing in ancient runic inscriptions in the form *alu*, and subsequently in Old Norse as *ǫl*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Through linguistic reconstruction it is possible to infer that the Common Germanic form of this word was **alúþ-*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] According to the third edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*, however, the origin of this word is 'uncertain and disputed'.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Research by Harald Bjorvand, however, has favoured the following explanation: the Germanic word **alú-þ-* descends from the Indo-European word ***olú-t-* (from an earlier Indo-European base **h₂elut-*), which originally meant 'golden or reddish colour'.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Other Indo-European words related to this root include Old Indic *aruṣá-* ('reddish'; the *r* comes from an earlier *l*, **alu-sá-*) and Old High German *elo* ('yellowy, pale yellow, reddish yellow, tawny').
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The Indo-European word **olú-t-* then came to refer specifically to ale because this is its colour, giving rise to both the Germanic word **alú-þ-* and the Ossetic word *æluton*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In this account, the Indo-European word **olú-t-* was also borrowed into the Finnic languages, giving Finnish *olut* and Estonian *õlu*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The relationship of similar words in the Slavonic languages (such as Old Bulgarian *olu* 'cider', Slovenian *ol* 'beer') and the Baltic languages (Lithuanian *alus*, Latvian *alus*, 'beer', Old Prussian *alu* 'mead') remains uncertain.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Ale was an important source of nutrition in the medieval world.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] It was one of three main sources of grain in the diet at the start of the fourteenth century in England, along with pottage and bread.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Scholars believe grains accounted for around 80% of the calorie intake of agricultural workers and 75% for soldiers - even nobles received around 65% of their calories from grains.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Small beer, also known as table beer or mild beer, which was highly nutritious, contained just enough alcohol to act as a preservative, and provided hydration without intoxicating effects.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Small beer would have been consumed daily by almost everyone, including children, in the medieval world, with higher-alcohol ales served for recreational purposes.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The lower cost for proprietors combined with the lower taxes levied on small beer inevitably led to the selling of some beer labeled "strong beer" that had actually been diluted with small beer.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Records from the Middle Ages show that ale was consumed in huge quantities.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In 1272, a husband and wife who retired at Selby Abbey were given 2 gallons of ale per day with two loaves of white bread and one loaf of brown bread.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Monks at Westminster Abbey consumed 1 gallon of ale each day.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In 1299, Henry de Lacy's household purchased an average of 85 gallons of ale daily and in 1385–86 Framlingham Castle consumed 78 gallons per day.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Brewing ale in the Middle Ages was a local industry primarily pursued by women.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Brewsters, or alewives, would brew in the home for both domestic consumption and small scale commercial sale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Brewsters provided a substantial supplemental income for families; however, only in select few cases, as was the case for widows, was brewing considered the primary income of the household.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] From the mid-17th century, strong ales became particularly fashionable.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] They were known by names such as Huff-Cap, Nippitate and Hum-Cup, so called because it caused "a humming sensation in the head".
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Strong ale, like wine, was typically decanted due to the high sediment content into small glasses, which were better suited to the high ABV ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Modern ale is typically fermented at temperatures between 15 and 24 °C (59 and 75 °F).
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] At temperatures above 24 °C (75 °F) the yeast can produce significant amounts of esters and other secondary flavour and aroma products, and the result is often a beer with slightly "fruity" compounds resembling those found in fruits, such as apple, pear, pineapple, banana, plum, cherry, or prune.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] When ale ferments, it naturally creates two prevalent byproducts, those being Sulfur Dioxide (SO2) and Hydrogen Sulfide (H2S).
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Each of these compounds affects the product in different ways, and each can be managed before and during the fermenting process to create different flavours and benefits for the ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Sulfur Dioxide is a product of some of the initial ingredients of ale and is produced during the fermentation of the wort.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Sulfur Dioxide helps to increase an ale's shelf life; however, it naturally occurs in foods when they become old, so many people react negatively to its smell and can even be viewed as an allergen in some countries.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] During the stages of fermentation of ale, the production of SO2 works as an antioxidant, a preservative, and, in addition, it works to fight bacteria.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Throughout the fermentation process, one of the ways in which brewers can control the levels of SO2 is through temperature during brewing, and another way to preserve that reaction is by tempering with the temperature at which the product is stored.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The cooler it is stored, the more SO2 is preserved, which helps the ale keep its flavour.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] When an ale becomes stale from oxidation, it loses its natural flavours; it could taste like any multitude of different undesirable things, depending on the initial flavour of the ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Some of the most common tastes for people are that of sherry, where the flavours have gotten negatively sweeter, or that of cardboard or paper, where it tastes stale and bland.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Hydrogen sulfide is another byproduct of fermentation.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In yeast strains, it helps the yeast grow and also works as an antioxidant later in the fermentation process.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Having a chemical compound including sulfur, however, means that it has a pungent smell that people often associate with rotten eggs, which can later affect the produced ale negatively, so producing and managing a finite amount of hydrogen sulfide is very important in the fermenting of ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] When controlled, the amount of H2S is generally unnoticeable and does not affect the overall smell or taste, but still does its job of keeping the shelf life of the ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] While making ale, sugar can be added either during the boiling stage or the fermenting stage; however, both times lead to similar outcomes, just at different levels of effectiveness.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The benefits of adding sugar to a brew can be to increase the overall APV levels of the brew and the flavour at the end of the brewing process.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Due to the higher APV, however, the body of the beer can often be left thinner, having a water-like consistency.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Both the factors of APV levels and flavour depend on what type of sugar you are adding, and oftentimes, when you add them in the process.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Generally, the later a sugar is added to the brew, the more prominent the flavour will be.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Sugar can be added so long as it is fermentable, which most common sugars are.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Generally, brewers will add different syrups, saps, honeys, and syrups to their ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Flocculation is the tendency for the yeast to conglomerate into large masses at the top and bottom of the fermentation tank at the end of the fermentation process.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] This selective trait in the yeast came about as the majority of the yeast that gets repurposed is that which aggregates and gets easily removed.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] This selective trait is gradually characterized in most yeast as the yeast that exhibits this behavior lasts a greater number of generations.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] "Real ale" is a British term, coined by the Campaign for Real Ale, for cask and bottle-conditioned beer.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The following list breaks the many various ales into separate, diverse categories.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ales listed are categorized into their respective style groups of origin and accompanied by information regarding the specific brew.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] For further classification, more comprehensive information can be found in the Brewers Association Style Guide.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In 18th-century England, brewers coined the term "pale ale" to distinguish this golden-hued ale from the more prevalent dark ales of the time.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The use of hops during fermentation introduces a distinctive bitter aroma, while the general absence of diacetyl groups and the presence of esters contribute to a sweeter and fruitier flavour compared to other ales.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The average alcohol by volume (ABV) of these ales ranges from 3.2% to 5.3%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Scotch ale, also known as "wee heavy", boasts an exceptionally malty taste accented by sweet malty undertones due to the heavy concentration of esters.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Generally low in bitterness, it exhibits a deep caramel colour, the shade of which may vary depending on the brewing techniques.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] They have a relatively high ABV, falling between 6.6% and 8.5%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] British-style summer ale is characteristically lighter in gold colour.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Filled with esters, this beer yields a fruity flavour and maintains a subdued yet weak profile in bitterness and hop.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ale is traditionally high in carbonation due to its respective brewing techniques.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Falling within the standard ABV range of 3.7% to 5.1% aligns with most beer's typical potency.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Old ale is classified as an intensely dark red ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] It is said to have a fruity aroma, with brewers occasionally adding caramel to sweeten the product.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The hop flavouring and bitterness of an old ale are relatively low compared to other types of categorized ales.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Adequately brewing an old ale involves an aging process spanning a few years.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Upon completion, it yields an extremely sweet drink comparable to wine.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The final ABV of the ale ranges from 5.0% to 9.3%, with higher percentages correlating to the amount of sugar added during fermentation.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Brown ale, distinguished by its dark hue, is commonly enriched with a blend of roasted and caramel malts, leading to a distinctively unique toffee-flavoured ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Both esters and diacetyl are found in low levels, contributing to the beer's unique taste.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ABV of brown ales typically ranges between 4.2% and 6.0%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Barley wine is known for its balance of flavour and high alcohol content.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ale's colour varies widely depending on the duration of its age, as its flavour profile evolves dramatically over time.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Low levels of diacetyl and carbonation are found in all barely wines, while esters are found in high quantities, contributing to a low bitter fruity flavour and aroma.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The flavours of barley wines are diverse, ranging from bread-like to hints of molasses and toffee.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] They have an unusually high ABV, ranging from 8.5% to 12.2%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] India pale ale, commonly shortened to IPA, is a hoppy pale ale which was originally shipped to colonial India.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Its high hop content prevented spoilage during the long sea course from England to India.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] IPA is full bodied and hoppy, it is amber coloured and usually somewhat opaque.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ABV of IPA can fall within the range of 4.5–20%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Amber ale is an American craft beer named after the hue it possesses from being flavoured using caramel malt.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ale is brewed with an assortment of hops and has a balanced flavour.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] It maintains a low level of esters and lacks any trace of diacetyl, leading to a moderately bitter and slightly fruity undertone.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ABV of amber ales ranges anywhere from 4.4% to 5.4%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Sour ale, more commonly known as wild ale, is characterized by a unique sour flavour, produced during fermentation when acid-producing bacteria like lactobacillus or acetobacter feed on sugars.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The acidity produced comes from mild concentrations of lactic or acetic acid and further develops during the aging process.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Utilizing wooden bourbon barrels imbued with either vanillin or sherry plays a crucial role in augmenting the beer's flavour complexity during aging.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The presence of esters and diacetyl fluctuates depending on the sought-after flavour profile of the brew.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The final ABV varies widely depending on the length and methods used during brewing.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Table beer typically has a low ABV of around 0.5% - 2.0%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Popular in Eastern Europe, these beverages are brewed with malt barley, wheat, oats, or rye.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] They are commonly flavoured with additive sugar and either orange or lemon peels to yield a citrus-like flavouring.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Session ale, named for its purpose of being enjoyed within a single "session" without inducing significant intoxication, features a low ABV, typically ranging from 3% to 5%.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Though they share similarities with table beers, they maintain a higher alcohol percentage.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] They are characterized by a balanced flavour profile, as the production method does not stray far from traditional ale brewing.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Esters may be present in medium quantities adding sweetness to the final flavour, while diacetyl is non-existent.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Most commercially available ales fall under the distinction of session ales due to their cost-effective ability to be brewed in mass.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The flavour profile of dark ale is characterized by a malty sweetness resulting from the abundance of esters in the brew.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] A discernible spiciness is attributed to yeast-derived phenolic compounds present in moderate quantities.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Depending on the brand, the beer tends to have a modest level of bitterness owing to the hops during fermentation.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The aroma of the brew is described as subtle yet persistent, due to phenol compounds.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] In terms of ABV, dark ale ranks notably high compared to other brews, ranging from 7.1% to 11.2%, often veiled by its diverse flavour profile.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Bière de Garde is a hybrid beer whose name translates from French to English as “Beer for Keeping”.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ale is low to moderate in esters and contains a similar malt sweetness to most other ales.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ale's ABV ranges from 4.4% to 8% and has a range of appearances, with its primary descriptions being “Light Amber, Chestnut Brown, or Red.” While most popular in France, this style has become much more frequent in the U.S. as the ale industry grows.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Irish red ale is characterized by its definitive amber or dark red hue, having an ABV ranging from 4.0% to 4.8%, and having a standard approachable bitterness, all of which make this ale highly sessionable.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Medium flavours of candy-like caramel malt distinguish the ale, and a tan foam forms at the top, due to the inclusion of roasted barley.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Originating in the Düsseldorf region of Germany, Altbier pays homage to traditional brewing methods, with "alt" meaning old in English.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The complexion ranges from light amber to a deep copper colour.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Esters are present in low quantities, which is attributed to their lightly citrus profile, while diacetyls are completely absent.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] The ale boasts a moderate level of bitterness owing to hops utilized in fermentation.
[src:humpty-dumpty/ale] Its ultimate ABV falls within the range of 4.6% to 5.6%, aligning typically with other ales.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] As a figure in nursery culture, the character appears under a variety of near-rhyming names, such as Lille Trille (Danish), Wirgele-Wargele (German), Hümpelken-Pümpelken (German) and Hobberti Bob (Pennsylvania Dutch).
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] As a character and literary allusion, Humpty Dumpty was referred to in several works of literature and popular culture in the nineteenth century.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Lewis Carroll in particular made him an animated egg in his 1871 book *Through the Looking-Glass*, while in the United States the character was popularised by George L.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Fox as a clown of that name in the Broadway pantomime musical *Humpty Dumpty* (1868).
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The rhyme is well known in the English language.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] It is a single quatrain with external rhymes that follow the pattern of AABB and with a trochaic metre, which is common in nursery rhymes.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] A manuscript addition to a copy of *Mother Goose's Melody* published in 1803 has the modern version with a different last line: "Could not set Humpty Dumpty up again".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] It was published in 1810 in a version of *Gammer Gurton's Garland*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] In 1841 an anthology of Latin and Greek translations of popular literature was published under the title *Arudines Cami* which included a version of the rhyme in Latin translation by Henry Drury.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Could put Humpty Dumpty on the wall again.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Evidence of an alternative American version closer to the modern received rhyme quoted above is given by William Carey Richards in the issue of a children's magazine for 1843, where he comments that he had come across it as a riddle when he was five years old and that the answer was "an egg".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] According to the *Oxford English Dictionary*, in the seventeenth century, the term "humpty dumpty" referred to a drink of brandy boiled with ale.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The riddle probably exploited, for misdirection, the fact that "humpty dumpty" was also eighteenth-century reduplicative slang for a short and clumsy person.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The riddle may depend upon the assumption that a clumsy person falling off a wall might not be irreparably damaged, whereas an egg would be.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The rhyme is no longer posed as a riddle, since the answer is now so well known.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Similar riddles have been recorded by folklorists in other languages, such as "Boule Boule" in French, "Lille Trille" in Swedish and Norwegian, and "Runtzelken-Puntzelken" or "Hümpelken-Pümpelken" in different parts of Germany—although none is as widely known as Humpty Dumpty is in English.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The rhyme does not explicitly state that the subject is an egg, possibly because it may have been originally posed as a riddle.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] There are also various theories of an original "Humpty Dumpty".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] One, advanced by Katherine Elwes Thomas in 1930 and adopted by Robert Ripley, posits that Humpty Dumpty is King Richard III of England, depicted as hunchbacked in Tudor histories and particularly in Shakespeare's play, and who was defeated, despite his armies, at Bosworth Field in 1485.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] In 1785, Francis Grose's *Classical Dictionary of the Vulgar Tongue* noted that a "Humpty Dumpty" was "a short clumsey [*sic*] person of either sex, also ale boiled with brandy"; no mention was made of the rhyme.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The name is also commonly applied to a person in an insecure position, something that would be difficult to reconstruct once broken, or a short and fat person.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Professor David Daube suggested in *The Oxford Magazine* of 16 February 1956 that Humpty Dumpty was a "tortoise" siege engine, an armored frame, used unsuccessfully to approach the walls of the Parliamentary-held city of Gloucester in 1643 during the Siege of Gloucester in the English Civil War.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] This was on the basis of a contemporary account of the attack, but without evidence that the rhyme was connected.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The theory was part of an anonymous series of articles on the origin of nursery rhymes and was widely acclaimed in academia, but it was derided by others as "ingenuity for ingenuity's sake" and declared to be a spoof.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The link was nevertheless popularized by a children's opera *All the King's Men* by Richard Rodney Bennett, first performed in 1969.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] From 1996, the website of the Colchester tourist board attributed the origin of the rhyme to a cannon recorded as used from the church of St Mary-at-the-Walls by the Royalist defenders in the siege of 1648.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] In 1648, Colchester was a walled town with a castle and several churches and was protected by the city wall.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The story given was that a large cannon, which the website claimed was colloquially called Humpty Dumpty, was strategically placed on the wall.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] A shot from a Parliamentary cannon succeeded in damaging the wall beneath Humpty Dumpty, which caused the cannon to tumble to the ground.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The Royalists (or Cavaliers, "all the King's men") attempted to raise Humpty Dumpty on to another part of the wall, but the cannon was so heavy that "All the King's horses and all the King's men couldn't put Humpty together again".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Author Albert Jack claimed in his 2008 book *Pop Goes the Weasel: The Secret Meanings of Nursery Rhymes* that there were two other verses supporting this claim.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Elsewhere, he claimed to have found them in an "old dusty library, [in] an even older book", but did not state what the book was or where it was found.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] It has been pointed out that the two additional verses are not in the style of the seventeenth century or of the existing rhyme, and that they do not fit with the earliest printed versions of the rhyme, which do not mention horses and men.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Fox helped to popularise the nursery rhyme character in a nineteenth-century pantomime on Broadway, where he figures as a clown.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] During the nineteenth century, too, Humpty Dumpty gave his name to a number of musical items, dependent either on the nursery rhyme or on the pantomime.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] They include Alfred Caldicott's glee of 1878 and E.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Sweeting's round of 1893, as well as Walford Davies' 1907 *Humpty Dumpty*, described as "a short cantata for children, consisting of a prelude, four short settings of the old nursery rhyme, and part of the scene between Alice and Humpty Dumpty (from *Alice Through the Looking-Glass*)".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] There were also purely musical items in the US, such as the 1875 galop by Harry R.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Jullian Gray and the 1900 schottische by H.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Humpty Dumpty makes an appearance in Lewis Carroll's *Through the Looking-Glass* (1871).
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] There Alice remarks that Humpty is "exactly like an egg", which Humpty finds to be "very provoking".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Alice clarifies that she said he looks like an egg, not that he is one.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] They then go on to discuss semantics and pragmatics when Humpty Dumpty says, "my name means the shape I am".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] James Joyce used the story of Humpty Dumpty as a recurring motif of the Fall of Man in the 1939 novel *Finnegans Wake*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] Humpty Dumpty has been used to demonstrate the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The law describes a process known as entropy, a measure of the number of specific ways in which a system may be arranged, often taken to be a measure of "disorder".
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] The higher the entropy, the higher the disorder.
[src:humpty-dumpty/humpty-dumpty] After his fall and subsequent shattering, the inability to put him together again is representative of this principle, as it would be highly unlikely (though not impossible) to return him to his earlier state of lower entropy, as the entropy of an isolated system never decreases.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] "**'Tis the Voice of the Lobster**" is a poem by Lewis Carroll that appears in Chapter 10 of his 1865 novel *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] It is recited by Alice to the Mock Turtle and the Gryphon.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] "'Tis the Voice of the Lobster" is a parody of "The Sluggard", a moralistic poem by Isaac Watts which was well known in Carroll's day.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] "The Sluggard" depicts the unsavory lifestyle of a slothful individual as a negative example.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] Carroll's lobster's corresponding vice is that he is weak and cannot back up his boasts, and is consequently easy prey.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] This fits the pattern of the predatory parody poems in the two Alice books.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] In 1886, Carroll wrote an altered and expanded version of the poem for the first theatrical adaptation of *Alice*.
[src:humpty-dumpty/tis-the-voice-of-the-lobster] In this version, a panther replaces the oyster.
